The Woodbury identity avoids forming the \(n_j \times n_j\) matrix \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_j\), reducing the per-study cost from \(O(n_j^3)\) (Cholesky) to \(O(n_j)\) (scalar operations plus a dot product). The dimensionality reduction from \(K + J + 1\) (CE) to \(K + 2\) (CHE) parameters is a major computational advantage, especially for meta-analyses with many studies.


4.3.4 CHE Score Functions
The CHE score for \(\boldsymbol{\beta}\) uses the marginal inverse \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_j^{-1}\):
\[
\mathbf{U}_j(\boldsymbol{\beta}) = \mathbf{X}_j^\top \boldsymbol{\Sigma}_j^{-1} \mathbf{r}_j, \qquad \mathbf{r}_j = \mathbf{y}_j - \mathbf{X}_j\boldsymbol{\beta}.
\tag{4.14}\]
The Stan implementation applies the Woodbury form of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_j^{-1}\mathbf{r}_j\) without ever constructing the full matrix:
if (compute_scores) {
  // S^{-1} r = r/a - (tau^2 * sum(r) / (a*c)) * 1
  vector[n_j] Sinv_r = r_j / a_j
                        - (tau2 * sum_r / (a_j * c_j))
                          * rep_vector(1.0, n_j);
  score_beta[j] = (block(X, start, 1, n_j, K)' * Sinv_r)';
}
Math-Code Mapping. The vector Sinv_r is \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_j^{-1}\mathbf{r}_j\) computed via Equation 4.12. The transpose operations produce a row vector score_beta[j] of length \(K\), corresponding to \(\mathbf{U}_j^\top\). Note that score_theta[j] is set to zero for the CHE model, since there are no explicit \(\theta_j\) parameters.


4.3.5 CHE Sufficient Statistics
The CHE generated quantities block exports sufficient statistics for R-side variance-component score computation:
// Sufficient statistics for R-side variance-component scores
vector[J] ss_sum_r;    // sum of residuals per study
vector[J] ss_sum_r2;   // sum of squared residuals per study
vector[J] ss_a;        // a_j = s_bar_sq_j + omega^2
vector[J] ss_c;        // c_j = a_j + n_j * tau^2
Math-Code Mapping. These four vectors, together with study_sizes (\(n_j\)), provide everything the R-side sandwich code needs to compute \(\partial \ell_j / \partial \tau^2\) and \(\partial \ell_j / \partial \omega^2\) without re-running the Stan model. This design keeps the Stan model focused on the beta-block scores while delegating variance-component score algebra to R.


4.3.6 R Extraction Code
# Extract posterior draws from a fitted CHE model
beta_draws  &lt;- .extract_draws(fit, "beta")   # S x K matrix
tau_draws   &lt;- .extract_draws(fit, "tau")    # S x 1 matrix
omega_draws &lt;- .extract_draws(fit, "omega")  # S x 1 matrix

# CHE has no explicit theta (integrated out in marginal likelihood)
# .extract_draws(fit, "theta") returns a zero matrix with a warning

# Posterior mean of omega^2 (Decision D20: Jensen-safe)
omega2_hat &lt;- mean(omega_draws^2)
Math-Code Mapping. Decision D20 specifies that \(\hat{\omega}^2 = S^{-1}\sum_s (\omega^{(s)})^2\), i.e., the posterior mean of the variance (not the square of the posterior mean of the standard deviation). This is Jensen-safe: \(E[\omega^2] \geq (E[\omega])^2\), and matches the convention used for \(\tau^2\) in the CE model. The omega block in .extract_draws() calls posterior::as_draws_matrix(x$fit$draws("omega")) and returns an \(S \times 1\) matrix.


4.3.7 Connection to Existing Software
The CHE model corresponds to metafor::rma.mv() with random = list(~ 1 | study, ~ 1 | obs) and to the three-level models of Cheung (2014) and Van den Noortgate et al. (2013). The key distinction is that bayesRVE estimates \((\boldsymbol{\beta}, \tau^2, \omega^2)\) jointly via full Bayesian inference, while the frequentist counterparts use REML.

9.4 NCP vs CP Parameterization

9.4.1 The Funnel Geometry Problem
The CE model introduces a hierarchical structure where \(\theta_j \sim \text{Normal}(0, \tau^2)\) and each \(\theta_j\) appears in the likelihood. When \(\tau\) is small, the posterior concentrates \(\theta_j\) near zero, creating a funnel-shaped geometry in the joint \((\tau, \boldsymbol{\theta})\) space. Hamiltonian Monte Carlo struggles with this geometry because the curvature varies sharply: the posterior is broad far from the funnel neck and extremely narrow near \(\tau \approx 0\). This mismatch between the global step size and local curvature produces divergent transitions.


9.4.2 Non-Centered Parameterization (NCP)
The non-centered parameterization (NCP) decouples the raw parameters from \(\tau\) by introducing auxiliary variables:
\[
\theta_{\text{raw},j} \sim \text{Normal}(0, 1), \qquad \theta_j = \tau \cdot \theta_{\text{raw},j}.
\]
In Stan, this is a two-block construction. The parameters block declares the raw variables, and the transformed parameters block applies the deterministic scaling:
// bm_ce_ncp.stan
parameters {
  vector[K] beta;
  vector[J] theta_raw;
  real&lt;lower=0&gt; tau;
}

transformed parameters {
  vector[J] theta = tau * theta_raw;
}
The model block then places a standard normal prior on theta_raw and the user-specified Half-\(t\) prior on tau. The likelihood uses theta[j] (the transformed parameter), so the sampling statement is identical to the centered version:
model {
  beta ~ normal(prior_beta_mean, prior_beta_sd);
  theta_raw ~ normal(0, 1);
  tau ~ student_t(prior_tau_df, prior_tau_location, prior_tau_scale);

  for (j in 1:J) {
    int start = study_starts[j];
    int n_j = study_sizes[j];
    real sd_j = sqrt(s_bar_sq[j]);
    segment(y, start, n_j) ~ normal(
      block(X, start, 1, n_j, K) * beta + theta[j],
      sd_j
    );
  }
}
The NCP works because the sampler explores \(\theta_{\text{raw},j}\), which has a unit-normal geometry regardless of \(\tau\). The funnel is eliminated from the sampling space.


9.4.3 Centered Parameterization (CP)
The centered parameterization (CP) samples \(\theta_j\) directly from \(\text{Normal}(0, \tau)\) in the model block. CP can be more efficient than NCP when the data are highly informative about each \(\theta_j\)—that is, when the within-study variance is small relative to \(\tau^2\)—because the posterior is far from the funnel geometry in this regime.
bayesRVE defaults to NCP (Decision D3), which is the safer choice for most meta-analytic applications where the number of effect sizes per study is modest. The parameterization = "cp" option invokes bm_ce_cp.stan, which places the prior directly:
// bm_ce_cp.stan (parameters and model blocks)
parameters {
  vector[K] beta;
  vector[J] theta;
  real&lt;lower=0&gt; tau;
}

model {
  beta ~ normal(prior_beta_mean, prior_beta_sd);
  theta ~ normal(0, tau);
  tau ~ student_t(prior_tau_df, prior_tau_location, prior_tau_scale);
  // ... likelihood identical
}


